    Creating new column as NewsPopularity based on shares

    In [18]:
    newsPopularity = []
for i in range(len(olDF)):
    if olDF[' shares'][i] <= 1500:
        newsPopularity.append('Poor')
    elif olDF[' shares'][i] > 1500 and olDF[' shares'][i] <= 10000:
        newsPopularity.append('Average')
    elif olDF[' shares'][i] > 10000 and olDF[' shares'][i] <= 50000:
        newsPopularity.append('Good')
    elif olDF[' shares'][i] > 50000 and olDF[' shares'][i] <= 100000:
        newsPopularity.append('Excellent')
    else:
        newsPopularity.append('Exceptional')

olDF = pd.concat([olDF, pd.DataFrame(newsPopularity, columns=['NewsPopularity'])], axis=1)

    Recommendations for Good Articles based on Exploratoty data analysis:  

      1. n_tokens_title should be between 6 - 17 words

      2. n_tokens_content should be less than or equal to 2000 words

      3. n_unique_tokens (rate of unique words in the content) should be between 0.4 - 0.8

      4. num_hrefs is between 1 and 50 referrence links

      5. num_imgs should between 1 - 30 images

      6. num_videos should be between 0 - 20 vidoes.

      7. average_token_length should be between 4 - 5

      8. The number of keywords in the metedata really influences the shares to a margin. The higher the value the better the shares

      9. The best articles ranking with highest share popularity are:
        1. Entertainment
        2. Technical
        3. World
        4. Business
        5. Lifestyle
        6. Social media

      10. Most popular articles are usually posted mainly on Wednesday (tuesday or thursday). Sundays and Saturdays (Weekends generally) are the worst days to publish an article.

    '''

numberOfRows = len(newsDF)

trainingRows = randomShuffledRows[0:int(numberOfRows * 0.75)]
testingRows = randomShuffledRows[int(numberOfRows * 0.75)+1:]

    Common Functions used by the regression models¶

    In [6]:
    '''
Function - to split the data into training and test rows 
'''
def splitData(inputDF, nTrainRows, nTestRows):
    X_train = inputDF.iloc[nTrainRows,0:-1]
    Y_train = inputDF.iloc[nTrainRows,-1]
    X_test = inputDF.iloc[nTestRows, 0:-1]
    Y_test = inputDF.iloc[nTestRows,-1]
    return X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test

'''
Fitting the regression models
'''
def fitModel(X_train,Y_train,modelName):
    if modelName == 'linear':
        model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    elif modelName == 'logistic':
        model = linear_model.LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs',max_iter=300)
    elif modelName == 'randomForest':
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 100)
    model.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    return model
    
'''    
Predicting the model on X_test 
'''
def predictModel(model, X_test):
    Y_Predict = model.predict(X_test)
    return Y_Predict
'''
Calculating the mean squared error 
'''
def meanSquareErr(Y_Predict, Y_test):
    return mean_squared_error(Y_Predict, Y_test)

'''
Calculating the R2 score 
'''
def r2Score(Y_Predict, Y_test):
    return r2_score(Y_Predict, Y_test)
'''
Calculating the AdjR2
'''
def adjR2Score(X_test,r2Score):
    n = X_test.shape[0]
    p = X_test.shape[1]
    return 1 - (1-r2Score) * (n-1)/(n-p-1)

'''
Calculating the accuracy_score    
'''
def accuracyScore(Y_Predict, Y_test):
    return str(100*accuracy_score(Y_Predict, Y_test))
    
'''
Fetching the top N features of a model 
'''
def getTopFeatures(model, noOfFeatures, featureNameList, modelName):
    modelTopFeaturesDF = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["FeatureName","Coefficient"])
    lenOfFeatures = 0
    if modelName == 'linear':
        featureCoef = model.coef_
        lenOfFeatures = len(featureCoef)
        for x in range(lenOfFeatures):
            modelTopFeaturesDF = modelTopFeaturesDF.append({"FeatureName":featureNameList[x],"Coefficient":featureCoef[x]}, ignore_index= True)
    elif modelName == 'logistic':
        featureCoef = model.coef_
        lenOfFeatures = len(featureCoef[0])
        for x in range(lenOfFeatures):
            modelTopFeaturesDF = modelTopFeaturesDF.append({"FeatureName":featureNameList[x],"Coefficient":featureCoef[0][x]}, ignore_index= True)
    elif modelName == 'randomForest':
        featureCoef = model.feature_importances_
        lenOfFeatures = len(featureCoef)
        for x in range(lenOfFeatures):
            modelTopFeaturesDF = modelTopFeaturesDF.append({"FeatureName":featureNameList[x],"Coefficient":featureCoef[x]}, ignore_index= True)
    topFeaturesDF = (modelTopFeaturesDF.iloc[(-modelTopFeaturesDF['Coefficient'].abs()).argsort()]).iloc[0:noOfFeatures,:]
    return topFeaturesDF

'''
Generating a new dataframe with top N features 
'''
def getDFWithTopFeatures(inputTopFeaturesDF, inputDF):
    dfWithTopFeatures = pd.DataFrame(data=None)
    for i in range(len(inputTopFeaturesDF)):
        dfWithTopFeatures[inputTopFeaturesDF.iloc[i,0]] = inputDF[inputTopFeaturesDF.iloc[i,0]] #LDA_01
    dfWithTopFeatures["shares"] = inputDF.iloc[:,-1]
    return dfWithTopFeatures

'''
Normalizing the input dataframe using standard_scaler 
'''
def getNormalizeDataFrame(inputDF):
    normalizedDF = inputDF.copy()
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    scaled_values = scaler.fit_transform(normalizedDF)
    normalizedDF.loc[:,:] = scaled_values
    return normalizedDF

    '''    
LinearRegression on the whole dataset without Normalization

mse = meanSquareErr(yPredict,yTest)
r2 = r2Score(yPredict,yTest)
adjR2 = adjR2Score(xTest, r2)
accScore = "NA"

resultsDF = resultsDF.append({"Description" : "LinearRegression",

                              "R2" : r2, 
                              "AdjR2" : adjR2,

                             )

LinearRegression on the whole dataset WITH Normalization

    '''
LinearRegression finding ideal number of features against adjusted R2
'''
newsNormalizedDF = getNormalizeDataFrame(newsDF)
xTrain, yTrain, xTest, yTest = splitData(newsNormalizedDF,trainingRows, testingRows)
reg = fitModel(xTrain,yTrain, modelName = 'linear')

resultTopFeatures = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Features","MSE","R2", "AdjR2", "AccuracyScore"])
for nfeatures in range(1,len(reg.coef_)):
    topFeaturesDF = getTopFeatures(reg, nfeatures, colNameList, modelName = 'linear')
    newsTopFeaturesDF = getDFWithTopFeatures(topFeaturesDF, newsNormalizedDF)
    xTrain, yTrain, xTest, yTest = splitData(newsTopFeaturesDF,trainingRows, testingRows)
    regTopFeatures = fitModel(xTrain,yTrain, modelName = 'linear')
    yPredict = predictModel(regTopFeatures, xTest)
    mse = meanSquareErr(yPredict,yTest)
    r2 = r2Score(yPredict,yTest)
    adjR2 = adjR2Score(xTest, r2)
    accScore = "NA"
    resultTopFeatures = resultTopFeatures.append({"Features" : int(nfeatures), 
                                                  "MSE" : mse ,
                                                  "R2" :r2 , 
                                                  "AdjR2" : adjR2,
                                                  "AccuracyScore" : accScore}
                                                  , ignore_index = True)

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(resultTopFeatures["Features"], resultTopFeatures["MSE"], marker = 'o', color = 'b')
ax.set_xlabel("No of Features",fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("MSE",color="blue",fontsize=14)
ax2=ax.twinx()
ax2.plot(resultTopFeatures["Features"], resultTopFeatures["AdjR2"], marker = '*', color = 'g')
ax2.set_ylabel("R2 score",color="green",fontsize=14)
ax3=ax.twinx()
ax3.plot(resultTopFeatures["Features"], resultTopFeatures["R2"], marker = '+', color = 'r')
plt.title('Linear Regression - No of Features vs MSE/R2 score')

    '''

    pcaTransformed = pca.fit_transform(newsX)

    Fitting PCA (n_components = 2) to see the distribution of the categorized shares.

    In [8]:
    '''
Principal Component Analysis (PCA) 

n_components = 2
'''

'''
Categorizing shares to Low ( < 25 percentile), Average ( > 25 and < 50), Good ( >50 and <75) and Excellent ( > 75) 
'''
newsShares = newsDF["shares"]
shareLabel = []
newsShares25per = np.percentile(newsShares,25)
newsShares50per = np.percentile(newsShares,50)
newsShares75per = np.percentile(newsShares,75)
for share in newsShares:
    if share < newsShares25per:
        shareLabel.append('Low')
    elif share >= newsShares25per and share < newsShares50per:
        shareLabel.append('Average')
    elif share >= newsShares50per and share < newsShares75per:
        shareLabel.append('Good')
    #share >= np.percentile(newsShares,75):    
    else:
        shareLabel.append('Excellent')
        
newsDF1 = pd.concat([newsDF, pd.DataFrame(shareLabel, columns=['share_performance'])], axis=1)
del newsDF1["shares"]

newsDF1["share_performance"] = pd.factorize(newsDF1['share_performance'])[0]


'''
Applying PCA (n_components = 2) for the normalized data
'''

newsNormalizedDF = getNormalizeDataFrame(newsDF)
newsX = newsNormalizedDF.iloc[:,0:-1]
newsY = newsDF1["share_performance"]

pca = PCA(n_components = 2)
pcaTransformed = pca.fit_transform(newsX)
print('Variance explained :',sum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
pcaDF = pd.DataFrame(data = pcaTransformed, columns = ["PCA1","PCA2"])

finalDf = pd.concat([pcaDF, newsY], axis = 1)

sns.scatterplot(x = 'PCA1', y = 'PCA2', hue = 'share_performance', data = finalDf)

    Applying Classifier Models

    In [99]:
    '''
Categorizing shares to Low ( < 25 percentile), Average ( > 25 and < 50), Good ( >50 and <75) and Excellent ( > 75) 
'''
newsShares = newsDF["shares"]
shareLabel = []
newsShares25per = np.percentile(newsShares,25)
newsShares50per = np.percentile(newsShares,50)
newsShares75per = np.percentile(newsShares,75)
for share in newsShares:
    if share < newsShares25per:
        shareLabel.append('Low')
    elif share >= newsShares25per and share < newsShares50per:
        shareLabel.append('Average')
    elif share >= newsShares50per and share < newsShares75per:
        shareLabel.append('Good')
    #share >= np.percentile(newsShares,75):    
    else:
        shareLabel.append('Excellent')
        
newsDF1 = pd.concat([newsDF, pd.DataFrame(shareLabel, columns=['share_performance'])], axis=1)
del newsDF1["shares"]

newsDF1["share_performance"] = pd.factorize(newsDF1['share_performance'])[0]


    Applying RandomForest Classification model on the dataset

    In [100]:
    '''
RandomForest Classifier (n_estimators)
'''
n_list = [1, 10, 50, 100, 200, 500, 700, 1000, 1500]
xTrain, yTrain, xTest, yTest = splitData(newsDF1,trainingRows, testingRows)
resultsRFC = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["No Of Estimators", "Accuracy"])
for n_estimator in n_list:
    rfClassifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimator)
    rfClassifier.fit(xTrain, yTrain)
    y_pred=rfClassifier.predict(xTest)
    rfcMSE = meanSquareErr(y_pred,yTest)
    rfcR2 = r2Score(y_pred,yTest)
    rfcAdjR2 = adjR2Score(xTest, rfcR2)
    accScore = accuracyScore(y_pred, yTest)
    resultsRFC = resultsRFC.append({"No Of Estimators":n_estimator, "Accuracy":accScore}, ignore_index = True)
    
plt.plot(resultsRFC["No Of Estimators"], resultsRFC["Accuracy"])
plt.xlabel('No of Estimators')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('Random Forest Classifier - No of Estimators vs Accuracy')

    '''
K-NearestNeighbour Classifier (n_neighbors)
'''
xTrain, yTrain, xTest, yTest = splitData(newsDF1,trainingRows, testingRows)
resultsKNN = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["No Of Neighbours", "Accuracy"])
for n_neighbor in range(1,200,5):
    knnClassifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = n_neighbor)
    knnClassifier.fit(xTrain, yTrain)
    y_pred=knnClassifier.predict(xTest)
    knnMSE = meanSquareErr(y_pred,yTest)
    knnR2 = r2Score(y_pred,yTest)
    knnAdjR2 = adjR2Score(xTest, rfcR2)
    accScore = accuracyScore(y_pred, yTest)
    resultsKNN = resultsKNN.append({"No Of Neighbours":n_neighbor, "Accuracy":accScore}, ignore_index = True)
    
plt.plot(resultsKNN["No Of Neighbours"], resultsKNN["Accuracy"])
plt.xlabel('No of Neighbours')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('KNN Classifier - No of Neighbours vs Accuracy')

    Conclusions

    1. Logistic Regression model has given higher accuracy of 65.53% for the dataset in predicting the number of shares.

    2. RandomForest Classifier has given accuracy of 41.79% when categorized the shares to Low, Avg, Good and Excellent based on the percentiles.

    3. For most of the regression models, the adjusted R2 remained the same, even when the model is built using the top 20 features based on the coefficients or importance values.
